			<h1 id="intro">Introduction</h1>

			<h2 id="preface">Preface</h2>
			
			<p>This is a reference grammar of <em>Qevesa</em>, a Northwestern Teralo language. Specifically, this grammar deals with the standard dialect as spoken on the west coast.</p>
			
			<h3 id="name">The name of the language</h3>
			<p>The language described here is known to native speakers as well as outsiders as <em>Qevesa</em>. In Qevesa the language may also be referred to as <em>Qeveli ke-sani</em>, ‘language of the Qeveli’, or <em>ëvaik sani</em>, ‘our language’. The word <em>qevesa</em> is itself an archaic term meaning ‘Qeveli speech’.</p>

<!--			<h3 id="ethnology">Ethnology</h2>
			<p>The Qevesa speaking world</p>-->
			
			<h3 id="demography">Demography</h3>
			<p>Qevesa is spoken today by approximately 7.7 million speakers, of which there are about 6.5 million in the <em>Republic of Qevelia</em>, about 900 000 in the <em>United Kingdoms of Semati</em>, and a further 200 000 in spread across central and south-western Teranië. As travel abroad is accessible, approximately a quarter of the population are polyglots. Furthermore, there are many multilingual speakers of minority languages spoken in some of the mountainous provinces.</p>

			<h3 id="dialects">Dialects</h3>
			<p>Qevesa is a Northwestern Teralo language, along with Keřesai and Voðirza. The current period, Modern Qevesa, started around the year 1200KE, following Middle Qevesa, which reached from 750KE to 1200KE. Prior to 750KE, Classical Qevesa (Këvesa) was spoken across the Kovask Empire. The modern standard (literary) language is based on the dialects spoken on the west coast of Qevelia; however the spoken language has a number of dialects, which can be broadly divided into two groups, Western Qevesa and Eastern Qevesa.</p>

<!--			<h3>History</h3>
			<p>Modern Qevesa is the result of an effort to combine the regional dialects of Old Qevesa into a single standard language. It is a member of the Teralo family of languages, and is a direct descendent of Proto-Teralo, the language spoken by the original inhabitants of the continent. Its nearest relatives are spoken in the far south east of Teralia, and Qevesa is geographically isolated due to the mountainous terrain of Qevelia.</p>
			<p>The geographical isolation is apparent in that Qevesa possesses some features that have disappeared in its neighbours, namely an active-stative morphosyntactic alignment and a fairly comprehensive set of cases.</p> -->
			
			<h2 id="abbreviations">Abbreviations</h2>
			<p>For convenience in transcribing interlinear glosses, the following abbreviations have been used in this document:</p>

