			</table>
			<p>Most consonants are realised as per the table above, with the exception that in many dialects, the unvoiced plosives may be aspirated. Furthermore, the following allophones exist:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>/h/ is normally not realised, except when following another consonant. It lengthens the previous vowel when preceding a consonant.</li>
				<li>/ɾ/ is realised as [r] when word-initial or word-final.</li>
				<li>/ð/ may be realised as a fricative or an approximant.</li>
				<li>[j] drops out before /i iː/, and [w] drops out before /u uː/</li>
				<li>[θ] drops out before /s ð/</li>
				<li>Affricates are often realised as their fricative counterparts when before another consonant.</li>
				<li>/s n ts/ before /j/ are realised as [ʃ ɲ tʃ]</li>
				<li>When between a consonant and a vowel, /j/ is often realised as [ĭ].</li>
			</ul>

