						</table>
						<p>The diphthongs that arise from the vowels are /ai au ei oi/, as well as /i-/ and /u-/ glides, which are realised as [w-] and [j-] respectively. Length is distinguished only where two adjacent vowels are the same, or where the vowel precedes <em>h</em> and another consonant. In this case, the <em>h</em> is always omitted.</p>

			<h2 id="syllable">Syllable Structure</h2>
			<p>Syllables can begin and end with any phoneme in the consonant inventory, or optionally none at all. Clusters of consonants can only occur at the syllable boundaries, with the exception of affricates and consonant–glide combinations (<em>i.e.</em> those that consist of consonant + /j/ or consonant + /w/). Words are divided into syllables according to the rule that <em>non-word-final consonants are always the onset of syllables unless followed by another consonant.</em> This leads to the following basic scheme:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>(C)V(C) is the basic syllable.</li>
				<li>CVCVC is realised as CV|CVC</li>
				<li>VCVC is realised as V|CVC</li>
				<li>VCCVC is realised as VC|CVC</li>
			</ul>

			<h1 id="morphology">Morphology</h1>

			<h2 id="verbs">Verbs</h2>
			<p>Qevesa is a language based on verbal triliteral roots, so the verb is the most complex and most important category. Verbs are marked for topical agreement, aspect and mood; other constructions are marked periphrastically.</p>
			<!--<p>Finite verbs may seem to be incredibly complex, as they are marked for up to eight categories:</p>
			<ol>
				<li>Dechticaetiative agreement</li>
				<li>Ergative agreement</li>
				<li>Accusative agreement</li>
				<li>Aspect</li>
				<li>Mood</li>
				<li>Polarity</li>
				<li>Evidentiality</li>
				<li>Telicity</li>
			</ol>
			<p>The first three categories consist of personal agreement with other arguments in the clause. Tense is not marked, but if required, will be indicated with adverbs for the specific time.</p>-->

			<h3 id="vconjugation">Conjugation</h3>
			<p>A Qevesa verb has eleven principal forms, corresponding to the <a href="#aspect">grammatical aspects</a> and the citation form, which is a non-finite form. Excluding verbal prefixes, a single verb can easily have over 11,000 forms — with a single prefix, over 40,000. These forms are comprised of the following affixes and clitics, in this order: <br /><span class="sc">stem.aspect-subject-mood</span></p>

			<h4 id="trclasses">Triliteral Root Classes</h4>
			<p>Qevesa is a language based on triliteral roots; a large percentage of the lexicon is derived from a considerably smaller base set of consonant groups. The system is highly regular, with the only irregularities occurring with certain consonants, especially /h/ and /j/, which are often lenited or otherwise omitted. This causes the triliteral roots to be divided into the following classes:</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Class I</strong> roots do not contain <em>-h-</em> or <em>-j-</em>, in any position. This is the largest group of triliteral roots.</li>
				<li><strong>Class II</strong> include all biliteral roots.</li>
				<li><strong>Class III</strong> roots are those which have <em>-h-</em> or <em>-j-</em> as the second consonant.</li>
				<li><strong>Class IV</strong> roots are those which have <em>-h-</em> or <em>-j-</em> as the third consonant.</li>
				<li><strong>Class V</strong> verbs include all verbs whose roots have <em>h-</em> or <em>j-</em> as the initial consonant.</li>
			</ul>

			<p>The citation form of each of these classes is as follows:</p>
			<dl>
				<dt>Class I</dt>
				<dd>C<sub>1</sub>uC<sub>2</sub>uC<sub>3</sub>u</dd>
				<dt>Class II</dt>
				<dd>C<sub>1</sub>uC<sub>2</sub>u</dd>
				<dt>Class III</dt>
				<dd>C<sub>1</sub>uC<sub>2</sub>C<sub>3</sub>u</dd>
				<dt>Class IV</dt>
				<dd>C<sub>1</sub>uC<sub>2</sub>uC<sub>3</sub>u</dd>
				<dt>Class V</dt>
				<dd>C<sub>1</sub>uC<sub>2</sub>uC<sub>3</sub>u</dd>
			</dl>

			<p>There are also irregular verbs which could be categorised into more than one class, but these are very rare. Examples include <em>jū</em> (to be, II &amp; V), <em>mū</em> (to not do, also II &amp; V), and <em>juzū</em> (to walk, IV &amp; V).</p>

			<h4 id="vaspect">Aspect</h4>

			<p>Aspect is possibly the most important grammatical category marked on the verb. Instead of tense, aspect is used to mark the temporal flow (or lack thereof) of verbs. Qevesa distinguishes between imperfective aspects (those that are ongoing, habitual, repeated or generally containing internal structure) and perfective aspects (those that are viewed as a single whole). There are two primary transfix patterns, corresponding to the imperfective and perfective aspects, and a number of secondary transfix patterns which indicate various subtle (mainly semantic) differences.</p>

			<h5 id="vimperfective">The Imperfective Aspects</h5>
			<p>The imperfective aspects are used to indicate the following:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>progressive or durative actions (the <em>dynamic imperfective</em>);</li>

				<li>states and activities posing the background for other (perfective) activities (the <em>background imperfective</em>);</li>
				<li>habitual activities (the <em>habitual imperfective</em>);</li>
				<li>multiple (iterative) activities (the <em>iterative imperfective</em>);</li>
				<li>non-resultative activities or states (the <em>irresultative imperfective</em>); and</li>

				<li>continuous states (the <em>stative imperfective</em>).</li>
			</ul>
			<p>These are marked as follows:</p>
			<table>
				<colgroup>
					<col width="30%"/>
					<col width="10%"/>
					<col width="12%"/>
					<col width="12%"/>
					<col width="12%"/>
					<col width="12%"/>
					<col width="12%"/>
				</colgroup>
				<tr>
					<th colspan="2" rowspan="2"/>
					<th colspan="5">Triliteral Root Class</th>

				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>I</th>
					<th>II</th>
					<th>III</th>
					<th>IV</th>
					<th>V</th>

				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Dynamic Imperfective</th>
					<th class="sc">dyn</th>
					<td>C<sub>1</sub><strong>a</strong>C<sub>2</sub><strong>i</strong>C<sub>3</sub></td>
					<td>C<sub>1</sub><strong>ai</strong>C<sub>2</sub></td>
					<td>C<sub>1</sub><strong>a</strong>C<sub>2</sub>C<sub>3</sub><strong>i</strong></td>
					<td>C<sub>1</sub><strong>a</strong>C<sub>2</sub><strong>i</strong>C<sub>3</sub></td>
