			<h4 id="vmood">Mood</h4>
			<p>Qevesa indicates mood through suffixes on the verb, some of which cause changes in its final vowel. At least one mood is mandatory.</p>
			
			<dl>
				<dt>The Declarative Mood</dt>
				<dd>The declarative mood is equivalent to the indicative mood, and indicates that the statement is true. It is formed by the addition of the suffix <em>-u</em>.</dd>

				<dt>The Conditional Mood</dt>
				<dd>The conditional mood is used to refer to an action or state that is dependent on a condition, and to refer to that condition. It is formed by the addition of the suffix <em>-ti</em>.</dd>

				<dt>The Intentive Mood</dt>
				<dd>The intentive mood is used to indicate that the speaker intends to perform the action. It is formed by the addition of the suffix <em>-di</em>.</dd>

				<dt>The Optative Mood</dt>
				<dd>The optative mood is used to indicate wishes and desires. It is formed by the suffix <em>-şi</em>.</dd>

				<dt>The Prohibitive Mood</dt>
				<dd>The prohibitive mood indicate that the action or state cannot occur. It is formed by the suffix <em>-me</em>.</dd>

				<dt>The Imperative Mood</dt>
				<dd>The imperative mood is used to indicate orders and commands. It is formed by the suffix <em>-ːl</em>; i.e. lengthening of the previous vowel and the addition of <em>-l</em>; long vowels are unmodified.</dd>
			</dl>

			<!--<h3>Other Auxiliary Constructions</h3>
			<p>The auxiliary verb has a number of regular constructions that are used to convey additional information.</p>-->


			<h3 id="vauxiliary">Auxiliary Constructions</h3>
			<p>There is a wide range of prefixes and proclitics which alter the meaning of a verb. Most of them are derivatives of other verbs or nouns, usually phonetic simplifications, although there are some which are independent lexemes. These can be grouped into several classes.</p>

			<h4 id="vcaus">The Causative</h4>
			<p>The causative is a special construction which takes its own arguments. It consists of the proclitic <em>pek</em>.</p>

			<h4 id="vneg">Negation</h4>
			<p>The negative mood has almost disappeared from Qevesa, and no longer exists as a modal suffix. Negation is instead expressed through the small number of negative verbs that exist. These verbs agree in aspect and mood with the verb they modify.</p>

			<table>
