			<h3 id="vderivation">Verbal Derivation</h3>
			<p>Qevesa is based on triliteral roots, so a large proportion of the lexicon is produced from a much smaller set of roots. Most nouns and modifiers are in fact derived from verb forms.</p>

			<h4 id="vnom">Nominalisations</h4>
			<p>Although there are many more nominalisations, the following are the most commonly used.</p>
			<dl>
				<dt>Concept</dt>
				<dd class="strong">C<sub>1</sub>eC<sub>2</sub>eC<sub>3</sub></dd>
				<dd>This is a general nominalisation representing the concept, process, activity or ability.</dd>

				<dt>Actor</dt>
				<dd class="strong">C<sub>1</sub>aC<sub>2</sub>oiC<sub>3</sub></dd>
				<dd>A person that performs the action.</dd>

				<dt>Patient</dt>
				<dd class="strong">C<sub>1</sub>oC<sub>2</sub>C<sub>3</sub>it</dd>
				<dd>Something that undergoes the action.</dd>

				<dt>Resulting Object</dt>
				<dd class="strong">C<sub>1</sub>iC<sub>2</sub>aC<sub>3</sub></dd>
				<dd>An object resulting from the action.</dd>

				<dt>Art</dt>
				<dd class="strong">C<sub>1</sub>eC<sub>2</sub>öC<sub>3</sub>a</dd>
				<dd>Names an art, skill, or science.</dd>

				<dt>Device</dt>
				<dd class="strong">C<sub>1</sub>eC<sub>2</sub>C<sub>2</sub>aC<sub>3</sub></dd>
				<dd>A non-human object that performs the action.</dd>

				<dt>Instrument</dt>
				<dd class="strong">C<sub>1</sub>iuC<sub>2</sub>iC<sub>3</sub></dd>
				<dd>A tool or object used to perform the action.</dd>

				<dt>Location</dt>
				<dd class="strong">aC<sub>1</sub>C<sub>2</sub>eC<sub>3</sub></dd>
				<dd>A place where the action is performed.</dd>

				<dt>Ergative Participle</dt>
				<dd class="strong">iC<sub>1</sub>aC<sub>2</sub>C<sub>3</sub>a</dd>
				<dd>Something which acts.</dd>

				<dt>Accusative Participle</dt>
				<dd class="strong">öC<sub>1</sub>üC<sub>2</sub>eC<sub>3</sub></dd>
				<dd>Something which is acted upon.</dd>
			</dl>

			<!--<p>Gender specific variants of the above nominalisations can be formed with the suffixes <em>-(i)ro</em> and <em>-(i)sse</em>.</p>-->

			<!--<h2>Compound Verbs</h2>
			<p>In addition to the basic verbs formed by the morphological processes described above, verbs can also be compounded to convey additional meaning. There are two primary methods of compounding: enclitics/suffixes that attach to the auxiliary verb; and proclitics/prefixes that attach to the primary verb. Enclitics on the auxiliary verb are normally used to indicate the manner in which the action is performed, and proclitics on the primary verb are normally used to indicate additional objects and the like. Both of these constructions are extremely productive, and in some (relatively rare) cases are used to create roots with four or more consonants.</p>-->

			<h2 id="nouns">Nouns</h2>
			<p>The declension of a Qevesa noun is generally quite regular; nouns are marked for case, number and possession. Other categories, such as gender, are seldom marked, although some nouns (such as pronouns and body parts) do possess so-called “natural gender”.</p>

			<h3 id="names">Proper Names</h3>
			<p>Names are treated differently from ordinary nouns in that they do not usually receive a suffixed case marker. Names are also not usually marked for number.</p>

			<h3 id="case">Case</h3>
			<p>Case markers in Qevesa are suffixes that attach to the head noun of a noun phrase.</p>
			<table>
				<caption>Case declension marking</caption>
				<colgroup>
					<col width="15%" />
					<col width="5%" />
					<col width="15%" />
					<col width="15%" />
					<col width="48%" />
				</colgroup>
				<tr>
					<th colspan="2">Case</th>
					<th>Postconsonantal</th>
					<th>Postvocalic</th>
					<th />
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Nominative</th>
					<th class="strong sc">nom</th>
					<td>-a</td>
					<td>-Ø</td>
					<td class="tl">Topic</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Ergative</th>
					<th class="sc">erg</th>
					<td colspan="2">-am</td>
					<td class="tl">Agent/Donor</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Accusative</th>
					<th class="sc">acc</th>
					<td colspan="2">-aş</td>
					<td class="tl">Patient/Recipient</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Dechticaetiative</th>
					<th class="sc">dct</th>
					<td>-ot</td>
					<td>-jot</td>
					<td class="tl">Theme</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Genetive</th>
					<th class="sc">gen</th>
					<td>-aik</td>
					<td>-k</td>
					<td class="tl">i.e. <em>of ...</em>, especially <em>of (a place)</em>; possession is usually indicated with possessive proclitic particle instead.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Essive</th>
					<th class="sc">ess</th>
					<td colspan="2">-ël</td>
					<td class="tl">Duration/Time; also indicates a temporary state of being; i.e. <em>as ...</em>, <em>being ....</em></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Instrumental (-Comitative)</th>
					<th class="sc">ins</th>
					<td colspan="2">-ëtti</td>
					<td class="tl">Tool, manner; i.e. <em>using ...</em>, <em>with ...</em></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Locative</th>
					<th class="sc">loc</th>
					<td colspan="2">-ëssi</td>
					<td class="tl">Internal location; i.e. <em>in(side) ...</em></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Adessive</th>
					<th class="sc">ads</th>
					<td colspan="2">-ëdi</td>
					<td class="tl">External location; i.e. <em>near ...</em>, <em>by ...</em>, <em>on ...</em></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Allative</th>
					<th class="sc">all</th>
					<td>-ovö</td>
					<td>-jovö</td>
					<td class="tl">Motion towards; i.e. <em>to(wards) ...</em></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Illative</th>
					<th class="sc">ill</th>
					<td colspan="2">-ëşte</td>
					<td class="tl">Motion from exterior to interior; i.e. <em>in(to) ...</em></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Ablative</th>
					<th class="sc">abl</th>
					<td colspan="2">-ësko</td>
					<td class="tl">Motion away from; i.e. <em>from ...</em></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Comparative</th>
					<th class="sc">cmp</th>
					<td colspan="2">-ënöc</td>
					<td class="tl">The standard by which something is compared.</td>
				</tr>
			</table>

			<h3 id="number">Number</h3>
			<p>Most nouns are countable and can be marked for number with a suffix that comes between the stem and the case marker. Qevesa possesses three numbers, singular, plural and quantitative. There are a small number of irregular nouns which are either uncountable or have number marked differently; these are noted where applicable in the <a href="index.php?page=conlangs/qevesa/lexicon">lexicon</a>.</p>
			<table>
				<caption>Marking of number</caption>
				<tr>
					<th>Singular</th>
					<th class="sc">sg</th>
					<td>-Ø</td>
					<td class="tl">Unmarked</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Plural</th>
					<th class="sc">pl</th>
					<td>-z</td>
					<td class="tl">Generic; used when a more numerals or quantifiers are not marked.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Quantitative</th>
					<th class="sc">qt</th>
					<td>-s</td>
					<td class="tl">Used with numerals and quantifiers.</td>
				</tr>
			</table>

			<h3 id="possession">Possession</h3>
			<p>Possession is normally marked by a proclitic particle, unless the possessor is a pronoun, in which case the pronoun is declined to the genetive case. The particle has two variants, one used with animate possessors and one used with inanimate possessors.</p>

			<table>
				<caption>Possessive particles</caption>
				<tr>
					<th>Animate</th>
					<th class="sc">an-pos</th>
					<td>zi</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Inanimate</th>
					<th class="sc">ia-pos</th>
					<td>zes</td>
				</tr>
			</table>

			<h3>Pronouns</h3>
			<p>Pronouns are roughly equivalent to nouns in terms of syntax and morphology, although they tend to have some irregular declensions.</p>

			<h4>Personal Pronouns</h4>
			<p>Most pronouns refer only to animate referents; a separate inanimate pronoun is used for inanimate referents. Pronouns are entirely without gender, and make no disctinction between male/female/neuter. There are two first person plural pronouns, an inclusive, which includes the listener, and an exclusive, which does not.</p>
			<table cellpadding="0">
				<caption>Personal Pronouns</caption>
