			<h3>Quantifiers</h3>
			<p>Quantifiers are similar to determiners. They do not agree in case with the noun they modify; as a rule, quantifiers are <em>always</em> marked in the genetive case.</p>
			<table>
				<tr>
					<th>Type</th>
					<th>Quantifier</th>
					<th>Prefix</th>
					<th />
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Paucal</th>
					<td>laifik</td>
					<td>laif-</td>
					<td class="em">a few of ...</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Plural</th>
					<td>vejik</td>
					<td>vej-</td>
					<td class="em">many of ...</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Partitive</th>
					<td>nilak</td>
					<td>nil-</td>
					<td class="em">some ...</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Selective</th>
					<td>përek</td>
					<td>për-</td>
					<td class="em">some ... / each ...</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Exhaustive</th>
					<td>veqek</td>
					<td>veq-</td>
					<td class="em">all of ...</td>
				</tr>
			</table>

			<h3>Interrogative Pronouns</h3>
			<p>The interrogative pronouns are listed in the following table; they decline as regular nouns to case and number.</p>
			<table>
				<tr>
					<th>Animate</th>
					<td>viz</td>
					<td class="em">who</td>
				</tr>
