			<h1 id="modifiers">Modifiers</h1>

			<h2 id="adjectives">Adjectives and Adverbs</h2>
			<p>Qevesa distinguishes between attributive and predicative adjectives. The former follow the pattern <em>CeCaCi</em> and do not decline to case or agree with the noun, although they can be modified with the polarity proclitics. Predicative adjectives are essentially modified forms of the verb.</p>
			<p>The attributive adjectives can be turned into adverbs by replacing the word final <em>-i</em> with <em>-a</em> and then casting it in the instrumental case. Like the attributive adjectives, adverbs can also be modified with the polarity proclitics.</p>

			<ul>
				<li><strong>Adjective</strong>: <em>pelati</em> beautiful</li>
				<li><strong>Adverb</strong>: <em>pelatatti</em> beauty, with beauty</li>
				<li><strong>Negative adverb</strong>: <em>pelatatti</em> without beauty</li>
			</ul>

			<h3 id="declension">Adjectival Declension</h3>
			<p>Predicative adjectives decline in a similar manner to verbs, although most conjugation involves the use of suffixes rather than transfixes. Although only aspectual marking is shown here, a predicative adjective can be marked with all of the categories that are applicable to a verb.</p>
			<h4 id="aimperfective">Imperfective Aspects</h4>
			<table>
				<tr>
					<th>Dynamic Imperfective</th>
					<th class="sc">dyn;ipfv</th>
					<td>C<sub>1</sub><strong>e</strong>C<sub>2</sub><strong>i</strong>C<sub>3</sub></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Background Imperfective</th>
					<th class="sc">bg;ipfv</th>
					<td>C<sub>1</sub><strong>e</strong>C<sub>2</sub>C<sub>3</sub><strong>e</strong></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Habitual Imperfective</th>
					<th class="sc">hab;ipfv</th>
					<td>C<sub>1</sub><strong>e</strong>C<sub>2</sub><strong>ü</strong>C<sub>3</sub><strong>i</strong></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Iterative Imperfective</th>
					<th class="sc">itr;ipfv</th>
					<td>C<sub>1</sub><strong>e</strong>C<sub>2</sub><strong>o</strong>C<sub>3</sub><strong>i</strong></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Irresultative Imperfective</th>
					<th class="sc">irr;ipfv</th>
					<td>C<sub>1</sub><strong>e</strong>C<sub>2</sub>C<sub>3</sub><strong>ai</strong></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Stative Imperfective</th>
					<th class="sc">stv;ipfv</th>
					<td>C<sub>1</sub><strong>ü</strong>C<sub>2</sub>C<sub>3</sub><strong>e</strong></td>
				</tr>
			</table>

			<h4 id="aperfective">Perfective Aspects</h4>
			<table>
				<tr>
					<th>Simple Perfective</th>
					<th class="sc">pftv</th>
					<td><strong>o</strong>C<sub>1</sub>C<sub>2</sub><strong>i</strong>C<sub>3</sub><strong>ai</strong></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Retrospective</th>
					<th class="sc">rspv</th>
					<td><strong>e</strong>C<sub>1</sub>C<sub>2</sub><strong>u</strong>C<sub>3</sub><strong>i</strong></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Inceptive</th>
					<th class="sc">icpv</th>
					<td><strong>i</strong>C<sub>1</sub>C<sub>2</sub><strong>o</strong>C<sub>3</sub><strong>oi</strong></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<th>Terminative</th>
					<th class="sc">tmtv</th>
					<td><strong>i</strong>C<sub>1</sub>C<sub>2</sub><strong>e</strong>C<sub>3</sub><strong>ü</strong></td>
				</tr>
			</table>


			<h3 id="comparison">Comparison</h3>

			<h4 id="acomparative">The Comparative Degree</h4>
			<p>The comparative degree is formed by placing the proclitic <em>opoş</em> before the adjective or adverb. The standard of comparison is formed by placing it in the comparative case.</p>

			<div class="gl">
				<p><strong>A</strong>-a <strong>B</strong>-enöc opoş-dülvenotuvo.</p>
				<div>
					<span class="gm"><strong>A</strong>-a</span>
					<span class="gx sc"><strong>A</strong>-nom</span>
				</div>
				<div>
					<span class="gm"><strong>B</strong>-enöc.</span>
					<span class="gx sc"><strong>B</strong>-cmp</span>
				</div>
				<div>
					<span class="gm">opoş=dülve-not-u-vo</span>
					<span class="gx">more=big<span class="sc">.stv;ipfv-3;inanim.dct.top-decl-ewts</span></span>
				</div>

				<p class="def">“A” is bigger than “B”.</p>
			</div>

			<h4 id="asuperlative">The Superlative Degree</h4>
			<p>The superlative degree is formed by the circumfix <em>o—eş</em>, which is placed around the adjective or adverb.</p>

			<div class="gl">
				<p><strong>A</strong>-a odülvenoteşuvo.</p>
				<div>
					<span class="gm"><strong>A</strong>-a</span>
					<span class="gx"><strong>A</strong><span class="sc">-nom</span></span>
				</div>
				<div>
					<span class="gm">o&gt;dülve-not&lt;eş-u-vo.</span>
					<span class="gx">&lt;most&gt;big<span class="sc">.stv;ipfv-3;inanim.dct.top-decl-ewts</span></span>
				</div>
				<p class="def">“A” is the biggest.</p>
			</div>

			<h4 id="adimunitive">The Dimunitive Degree</h4>
			<p>A dimunitive degree also exists, although is used far less often. It consists of  the proclitic <em>mëş</em> or as the circumfix <em>mi—eş</em>. The proclitic is used for the dimunitive comparative, and the circumfix for the dimunitive superlative.</p>

			<div class="gl">
				<p><strong>A</strong>-a <strong>B</strong>-enöc mëş-dülvenotuvo.</p>
				<div>
					<span class="gm"><strong>A</strong>-a</span>
					<span class="gx sc"><strong>A</strong>-nom</span>
				</div>
				<div>
					<span class="gm"><strong>B</strong>-enöc.</span>
					<span class="gx sc"><strong>B</strong>-cmp</span>
				</div>
				<div>
					<span class="gm">mëş=dülve-not-u-vo</span>
					<span class="gx">less=big<span class="sc">.stv;ipfv-3;inanim.dct.top-decl-ewts</span></span>
				</div>
				<p class="def">“A” is not as big as “B”.</p>

				<p><strong>A</strong>-a midülvenoteşuvo.</p>
				<div>
					<span class="gm"><strong>A</strong>-a</span>
					<span class="gx"><strong>A</strong><span class="sc">-nom</span></span>
				</div>
				<div>
					<span class="gm">mi&gt;dülve-not&lt;eş-u-vo</span>
					<span class="gx">&lt;least&gt;big<span class="sc">.stv;ipfv-3;inanim.dct.top-decl-ewts</span></span>
				</div>
				<p class="def">“A” is the least biggest.</p>
			</div>
		
		</div>
	</body>
</html>
